Seder Chalitza: The mitzvah of chalitzah requires three judges. Therefore, the rabbi of the city joins two of the prominent people as judges and adds two more as additional participants. These should not be converts or blind individuals, even if they are blind in only one eye, as it is written "before the eyes of the elders." Some are stringent that they should have no blemish at all, and it is good that they all engage in repentance. However, if they can see with both eyes but their vision is poor, or they cannot see without glasses, we do not concern ourselves with this. They should not receive payment for the chalitzah, but for the additional participants, we are not concerned if they receive payment.

There should be no familial closeness between them, neither for the yavam (levirate husband) and the yevamah (levirate wife), and according to the law, the disqualifying closeness extends only up to second-degree relatives. However, if possible, it is preferable that even fourth-degree relatives should not be involved. Beyond this, we are not concerned at all. Similarly, regarding the additional cases, it suffices up to second-degree relatives, and their wives should also not be disqualifyingly close to each other, meaning up to second-degree relatives. All the more so, none of them should be disqualified from serving as a judge.

On the evening before the chalitzah, between Mincha and Ma'ariv, all the judges gather in one place, and the rabbi says to them, "Let us go and designate a place for tomorrow's chalitzah." They go to the place where the chalitzah will take place and sit for a short time in the manner they will sit the next day: the three judges on one bench, the rabbi in the middle, the senior judge on his right, and the junior judge on his left; the other two judges sit to the side. The presence of the additional judges is not essential if they do not come to designate the place, as the main chalitzah requires only three judges. They then say, "We hereby designate this place for tomorrow's chalitzah." If the chalitzah is to take place on Sunday, they do not designate the place on Shabbat, but only on Friday.

The place needs to be in a prominent location in the city, meaning in a well-known place, and the custom is to perform the chalitzah ceremony in the largest synagogue or study hall in the city. Chalitzah is not performed on Fridays or the eve of festivals unless under pressing circumstances.

And then, when they set a time, they send the beadle to warn the yevama (the brother's widow) not to eat any food or drink any beverage the next day until after the chalitza (ceremony of removing the shoe). She should also not rinse her mouth in the morning when she rises from her bed, not speak much, and not clean her teeth. They also instruct the yavam (the brother-in-law) to wash his right foot and clean it, and to cut his nails so that it will be easy to wash it the next day. He should also wrap it in a cloth. Additionally, they teach the yavam and the yevama the verses they need to recite during the chalitza. The next day, after the morning prayer, the beadle warns them once again about all these matters. They prepare two valid witnesses who are not related to each other, to the judges, or to the yavam and yevama, to stand by during the chalitza. Even though this is not required by law, this is the custom.

The chalitzah is performed in the morning immediately after the prayer so that there will be a large congregation. Immediately after the prayer, they clear the entire area where the chalitzah will take place of utensils and people, and they make separations with benches between the place of the chalitzah and the rest of the congregation. In such a manner that in the place of the chalitzah, only the judges, the witnesses, the yavam (levir), and the yevamah (levirate widow) will be present. A bench is placed opposite the place of the three judges where the yavam and yevamah will sit.

The judges sit in their designated places as established yesterday, the three together and the additional ones beside them. The yavam (levirate husband) and the yevama (levirate wife) come and stand before the rabbi and the judges. The rabbi instructs them to sit on the bench opposite them, and they sit. Two witnesses stand over them, one on this side and one on that side, and they caution her not to spit before the designated time. If she wishes to spit, she should do so within her garment. Therefore, it is customary for her mouth to be wrapped. Additionally, it is proper for both the yavam and the yevama to be wrapped like mourners. This is also recorded in the Shulchan Aruch. However, in our community, we do not practice wrapping even in mourning, as stated in Yoreh De'ah, section 376.

Before the rabbi instructs them to sit while they are still standing before him, the rabbi must investigate all necessary matters: whether they are adults, whether they recognize that she is the widow of the deceased and he is the brother of the deceased, whether it has been ninety days since the day of death, whether the levir (yavam) is not mute, deaf, insane, or blind (for if there is another brother, a blind one should not perform the chalitzah), and similarly, whether she is not deaf, insane, or mute. Additionally, it should be examined whether they are not left-handed—she with her hand and he with his foot—whether his foot is not bent backward or turned to the side, and whether he does not walk on his toes. They should also investigate whether the deceased left no offspring or offspring's offspring, and inquire whether he is the eldest brother or if he is the only brother. They should verify if they ever lived together in the world (and if he is a convert, whether both were conceived and born in holiness). In all these matters, complete testimony is not required; even a relative or a woman is believed.

When the yavam (levirate husband) and the yevamah (levirate wife) are seated on the bench, the rabbi asks the yavam what his intention is, and he responds that he wishes to perform chalitzah (the ceremony releasing him from the levirate marriage). The rabbi then asks the yevamah if she desires chalitzah, and she says yes. The rabbi instructs them to stand, and they stand before the judges, with the yevamah standing to the right of the yavam. The rabbi tells him, "Know that according to Torah law, if you wish to perform yibbum (levirate marriage), you may do so (even if he has a wife, he should tell me this, and add that there is no prohibition against having two wives according to the commandment of the Torah)." The yavam replies, "I do not wish to perform yibbum, only chalitzah." (What is written in Pitchei Teshuvah, section 10, in the name of the Ketzot HaChoshen citing the Yam Shel Shlomo, that when he has a wife he should not say this — Heaven forbid to change this. The Yam Shel Shlomo himself wrote this at the end of chapter 48 in the order of chalitzah.)

It is necessary that both the yavam (levir) and the yevamah (levirate widow) are aware that through this act of chalitzah, she becomes permitted to marry someone else. The rabbi should inform them to have the intention for the mitzvah, as it is through the act of chalitzah that she is permitted to the general public, to marry whomever she wishes except for a Kohen (priest). (Additionally, the rabbi should instruct them not to respond twice with "yes" or twice with "no" to the questions asked of them).

The rabbi asks the yavam (levir) if he is being coerced into this chalitzah (ceremony of release from levirate marriage) and he responds no. The rabbi then asks if he swore an oath, made a vow, gave a financial guarantee, or accepted upon himself to perform the chalitzah or, conversely, not to perform it. The yavam responds, "I did not swear an oath, make a vow, give a financial guarantee, nor did I accept upon myself to perform the chalitzah or not to perform it." The rabbi then says, "Perhaps you swore an oath or made a vow; we will annul the vow or the oath, etc., based on your regret for it as a whole." The yavam then responds, "If I swore an oath or made a vow, I regret it entirely." The judges then say to him three times, "It is permitted to you" (similar to the procedure in a get, a divorce document).

The rabbi asks him if he perhaps issued a declaration of protest (moda'ah) regarding the chalitzah. The rabbi understands what the matter of issuing a protest is. Therefore, he nullifies before us all such declarations and disqualifies any witnesses who would testify that he issued a declaration of protest about this chalitzah. Thus, the yavam (levir) says: "I hereby nullify all declarations of protest and any declarations about declarations forever that I have issued regarding this chalitzah, and all things I have issued which, when fulfilled, would cause this chalitzah to be nullified—they are hereby nullified. And I also testify about myself that I have not issued anything that would disqualify this chalitzah because of it, and I hereby disqualify any witness or witnesses who would testify that I issued or said anything that would nullify this chalitzah or weaken its validity because of it."

The rabbi should ask the yevama (the widow subject to levirate marriage) if she has not eaten or drunk today and if she has not rinsed her mouth. She should respond, "I have not eaten, I have not drunk, and I have not rinsed my mouth." He should also ask if she will perform the act of chalitza willingly, and she should respond, "Yes." (In general, they should be careful not to end up with an invalid chalitza.)

The rabbi should take the shoe and examine it to ensure it is made according to the proper specifications, and then he should acquire it for the yavam (levir). He should say to him, "I am giving you this shoe as a complete gift," and the yavam should take the shoe and lift it three handbreadths. If he did not do so, it is still valid, for if she performed the chalitzah with a shoe that does not belong to him, her chalitzah is valid. The rabbi should check that there is no mud on the shoe and ensure that the shoe is clean.

The rabbi asks whether his right foot is clean, and the rabbi examines his foot to ensure it is free from any dirt. It is the commandment for the brother-in-law (yavam) to tie the strap of the shoe above his calf. (What we wrote that the rabbi should give the shoe to the brother-in-law as a gift applies when the shoe belongs to the community or to the rabbi himself. If the shoe belongs to someone else, that person should give it as a gift to the brother-in-law. If the shoe belongs to the sister-in-law (yevamah), for instance, if she bought it with her own money, she should give it to him as a gift. In all these cases, there is no hindrance after the fact, as we have written.)

And the yavam (levirate husband) should put the shoe on his right foot, on his bare foot without stockings, so that it is close to his flesh. Alternatively, the rabbi may put it on him, and there is no concern about this as long as it is seen that the shoe fits the size of his foot. Even if it does not fit perfectly, such as if it is slightly larger than the size of his foot, it is acceptable, as long as he is able to walk in it without tying the straps. For if he cannot walk in it at all without the straps, we have already written in the name of the Maharshal in Yam Shel Shlomo that we do not perform chalitzah with it, and we have explained this in section 26, see there.

The order of the bindings is as follows: When one puts on the shoe, he should insert all three hooks into their loops, and afterwards wrap the straps three times around the foot in this manner. As we have already written, there are holes in the shoe. Therefore, he should pass the right strap to the left side of the foot and the left strap to the right side, and thread them through the loops until they reach the back of the foot through the lower hole. He should place the straps there, aligned next to each other, and then wrap around the foot a second time through the upper loops until they reach the back of the foot in the upper hole, and place them there as well, aligned next to each other. Afterwards, he should wrap a third time around the foot until they reach above the loops on the front of the foot, which is called "shinvayim" (and we have already explained that the Shulchan Aruch does not agree with wrapping on the shinvayim, only on the foot itself). He should make two knots and a bow on top, and the second knot should not be tied too tightly so that the yevama (the widow awaiting levirate marriage) can untie it (Levush). We have already written that some make small loops between the hooks and between the loops so that when wrapping the straps around the foot, they can be inserted through these loops and wrapped better. (And those who make inner loops also on the sides of the shoe should insert the straps through these inner loops as written in Pesach section 59).

After putting on the shoe, he should lift his garments and walk before the judges for at least four cubits. They should see that he walks properly, that the straps are not above the ankle, and they should also see that his right leg is indeed his right leg as is customary for every person, and that he is not left-footed.

And afterward, they position the yavam (levir) next to a wall, leaning against a board or pillar, ensuring that he does not lean so much that if the board were to be removed he would fall, for this would not be considered standing. Rather, he should lean slightly and place his right foot on the ground. They instruct them another time to intend with this action to release her from her levirate bond so that she would be permitted to marry any man she wishes.

The Rabbi prompts the yevama (widow) and she says, "My brother-in-law refuses to establish a name for his brother in Israel; he does not want to perform levirate marriage with me" (these three phrases should be said in one breath). She then explains her words in the commonly spoken vernacular after having said them in the Holy Tongue. Afterwards, the Rabbi prompts the yavam (brother-in-law) — "I do not wish to take her" (pronouncing the final "he" clearly). He then explains his words in the commonly spoken vernacular.

Afterward, his brother's widow shall approach him face to face, and he stands close to the platform with his foot slightly pressed against the ground. The widow shall kneel and untie the straps from the sandal with her right hand specifically, without any assistance from the left hand. Once she has finished untying the straps and completely removed the laces, she begins by unfastening the hooks from the loops, starting with the bottom hook, then the middle one, and finally the top one. She shall then grasp the back of his foot with her left hand, lift the foot from the ground, and with her right hand, slip off the sandal from the heel. Immediately, she shall remove the sandal from his foot, doing this only with her right hand without any assistance from the left hand (since with her left hand she holds his foot in the air as mentioned). Additionally, the brother-in-law shall not assist her with his hands or feet. Immediately after she has removed the sandal from his foot, she throws the sandal to the ground and casts it far away.

And afterwards, the rabbi tells her to gather a lot of saliva in her mouth, not through hawking, swallowing, yawning, or sneezing, but clean saliva. She should stand facing the yavam (levirate husband) face to face and spit in front of him onto the ground. The judges should see the saliva as it leaves her mouth until it reaches the ground, and the yavam should also see this.

Afterward, the rabbi reads out to her the verse: "So shall be done to the man who does not build up his brother's house, and his name shall be called in Israel, 'The house of him whose shoe was removed.'" She then says three times, "The shoe is removed!" And the judges and all those standing there respond after her, "The shoe is removed! The shoe is removed! The shoe is removed!"

Afterward, the yavam (the brother-in-law) returns the shoe to the rabbi and gifts it to him. The rabbi then lifts it three handbreadths, and the judges say, "May it be God's will that the daughters of Israel shall no longer come to the need of chalitzah or yibbum."

When the judges stand up from their place, the rabbi should say: "Blessed is He who sanctified us with the commandments and statutes of Abraham our forefather." This should be said without mentioning God's name and kingship because this is not found in the Talmud. It comes from the divorce rituals of the Ashkenazim, and the basis for this is from what our sages said in the chapter on the covering of the blood: "In the merit of Abraham saying, 'I will not take from a thread to a sandal strap,' his descendants merited the shoe of Halitzah." This is written in the Shulchan Aruch and the Levush. However, I am puzzled because this is not found in the Talmud. In the Talmud there (Chullin 89a), this is interpreted regarding the strap of tefillin. However, it is found in the Midrash Bereshit, chapter 43, where it states: Rabbi Abba bar Mammal said: "The Holy One, blessed be He, said to him, 'You said, etc., "to a sandal strap," by your life, I will give your descendants the commandment of Halitzah, as you said, "and she shall remove his shoe from his foot."'"

The text of the Chalitzah document has already been written, but at the end of the procedure of Chalitzah, it is written in the name of Mahari Margalit that we do not have the custom to write a Chalitzah document because since she performs Chalitzah in public, she does not need a document for proof. And the Yeshuot Yaakov wrote that it is good to write it, and there are procedures that include decreeing against those who cast aspersions on the Chalitzah, similar to a get (divorce document), but we do not have such a custom. It has already been explained that Chalitzah is not performed at night, nor on Shabbat and Yom Tov, but it is performed on Chol Hamoed (the intermediate days of the festival). On Erev Shabbat and Erev Yom Tov, Chalitzah is only performed in pressing circumstances. 

Slik B'Siyata D'Shmaya (Finished with the help of Heaven).
